2
00:00:15,165 --> 00:00:16,365
(RADIO JINGLE PLAYING)

3
00:00:16,445 --> 00:00:18,805
ANNOUNCER: It is a beautiful day
in Chicago today.

4
00:00:18,885 --> 00:00:21,364
Temperatures expected
to reach the upper 70s.

5
00:00:21,885 --> 00:00:23,725
Right now, 75 at the lakefront,

6
00:00:23,805 --> 00:00:26,284
74 at Midway, 73 at O'Hare.

7
00:00:26,606 --> 00:00:28,805
And now, up in the sky,

8
00:00:28,885 --> 00:00:31,005
- Don Nelson with Sky View traffic.
- KATIE: Ferris?

9
00:00:31,085 --> 00:00:32,044
NELSON: Thanks.
KATIE: Ferris?

10
00:00:32,126 --> 00:00:33,205
NELSON: We've got
scores of accidents.

11
00:00:33,285 --> 00:00:34,325
KATIE: Tom!

12
00:00:34,446 --> 00:00:35,845
(DOG BARKING)

13
00:00:37,326 --> 00:00:39,004
- TOM: What's the matter?
- It's Ferris.

14
00:00:39,086 --> 00:00:40,885
- What? What's wrong?
- What's wrong? For Christ's sake

15
00:00:40,965 --> 00:00:42,685
look at him, honey.

16
00:00:43,965 --> 00:00:45,204
TOM: Ferris?

17
00:00:48,245 --> 00:00:52,005
He doesn't have a fever, but he says his
stomach hurts and he's seeing spots.

18
00:00:52,085 --> 00:00:53,884
TOM: What's the matter, Ferris?

19
00:00:54,925 --> 00:00:55,924
Papa?

20
00:00:56,006 --> 00:00:58,605
Honey, feel his hands.
They're cold and clammy.

21
00:01:03,285 --> 00:01:05,165
I'm fine.

22
00:01:05,245 --> 00:01:07,404
- I can get up.
- No.

23
00:01:07,486 --> 00:01:09,005
- I have a test today.
- KATIE: No.

24
00:01:09,085 --> 00:01:10,844
You...

25
00:01:10,926 --> 00:01:13,364
I have to take it.

26
00:01:13,445 --> 00:01:16,604
I want to go to a good college,
so I can have a fruitful life.

27
00:01:16,686 --> 00:01:19,084
KATIE: Honey, you're not going
to school like this, now.

28
00:01:19,166 --> 00:01:21,564
Fine. What's this? What's his problem?

29
00:01:23,045 --> 00:01:25,524
- He doesn't feel well.
- Yeah, right.

30
00:01:25,606 --> 00:01:27,604
Dry that one out,
you can fertilize the lawn.

31
00:01:27,686 --> 00:01:30,084
Jeanie? Is that you?

32
00:01:31,445 --> 00:01:34,085
Jeanie? I can't see that far.

33
00:01:34,526 --> 00:01:37,724
(PANTING) Jeanie? Jeanie, I...

34
00:01:41,045 --> 00:01:42,404
Bite the big one, Junior.

35
00:01:42,486 --> 00:01:44,484
KATIE: Thank you, Jeanie.
You get to school.

36
00:01:44,686 --> 00:01:46,964
Wait, you're letting him stay home?

37
00:01:47,286 --> 00:01:49,284
I can't believe this.
If I was bleeding out my eyes

38
00:01:49,365 --> 00:01:51,844
you guys would make me go to school.
This is so unfair.

39
00:01:51,926 --> 00:01:54,444
Jeanie, please don't be upset with me.

40
00:01:54,605 --> 00:01:56,725
You have your health. Be thankful.

41
00:01:58,926 --> 00:02:00,124
(MOANS)

42
00:02:00,245 --> 00:02:01,685
(BOTH GROANING)

43
00:02:01,845 --> 00:02:04,285
That's it. I want out of this family.

44
00:02:06,565 --> 00:02:08,764
FERRIS: I'm okay. I'll just sleep.

45
00:02:10,205 --> 00:02:12,485
Maybe I'll have an aspirin around noon.

46
00:02:12,565 --> 00:02:15,284
KATIE: Now, listen,
I'm showing some houses to that,

47
00:02:15,365 --> 00:02:17,605
that family from Vermont today.
So I'll be in the area.

48
00:02:17,685 --> 00:02:21,124
Now, my office will know just where
I am if you need me, okay?

49
00:02:21,566 --> 00:02:23,044
- Okay.
- Okay.

50
00:02:23,125 --> 00:02:24,804
I'll check on you too, pal.

51
00:02:24,885 --> 00:02:29,044
It's nice to know
that I have such loving, caring parents.

52
00:02:29,366 --> 00:02:31,644
You're both very special people.

53
00:02:36,285 --> 00:02:38,404
KATIE: Now, you get better, pumpkin.

54
00:02:38,805 --> 00:02:40,444
Okay, pumpkin.

55
00:02:41,446 --> 00:02:43,044
I'll be home at 6:00 sharp.

56
00:02:43,125 --> 00:02:45,445
If you need anything, call.

57
00:02:45,525 --> 00:02:47,244
Ringy-dingy.

58
00:02:50,165 --> 00:02:53,125
- We love you, sweetie.
- I love you, too.

59
00:02:54,206 --> 00:02:55,845
(MUMBLING GIBBERISH)

60
00:02:55,925 --> 00:02:57,684
TOM: Call if you need us.

61
00:03:05,765 --> 00:03:07,004
They bought it.

62
00:03:07,125 --> 00:03:09,084
(ROCK MUSIC PLAYING ON TV)

63
00:03:10,645 --> 00:03:11,924
(WHIRRING)

64
00:03:13,645 --> 00:03:15,244
(GLASS SHATTERING)

65
00:03:17,246 --> 00:03:18,325
Incredible.

66
00:03:18,405 --> 00:03:20,444
One of the worst performances
of my career

67
00:03:20,526 --> 00:03:22,804
and they never doubted it for a second.

68
00:03:27,925 --> 00:03:31,564
How could I possibly be expected
to handle school on a day like this?

69
00:03:33,605 --> 00:03:35,644
(LOVE MISSILE F1-11 PLAYING)

70
00:03:41,126 --> 00:03:43,445
This is my ninth sick day this semester.

71
00:03:43,765 --> 00:03:46,804
It's getting pretty tough
coming up with new illnesses.

72
00:03:47,286 --> 00:03:50,244
If I go for 10, I'm probably
gonna have to barf up a lung.

73
00:03:50,325 --> 00:03:52,244
So I better make this one count.

74
00:03:54,325 --> 00:03:57,204
The key to faking out the parents
is the clammy hands.

75
00:03:57,365 --> 00:04:00,604
It's a good non-specific symptom.
I'm a big believer in it.

76
00:04:01,885 --> 00:04:05,444
A lot of people will tell you that
a good, phony fever is a dead lock.

77
00:04:05,526 --> 00:04:09,765
But, you get a nervous mother,
you could wind up in a doctor's office.

78
00:04:09,845 --> 00:04:11,764
That's worse than school.

79
00:04:12,605 --> 00:04:14,445
You fake a stomach cramp

80
00:04:14,525 --> 00:04:17,484
and when you're bent over,
moaning and wailing,

81
00:04:17,965 --> 00:04:19,525
you lick your palms.

82
00:04:19,605 --> 00:04:21,604
It's a little childish and stupid,

83
00:04:21,685 --> 00:04:23,044
but then, so is high school.

84
00:04:25,006 --> 00:04:26,564
Life moves pretty fast.

85
00:04:28,885 --> 00:04:32,444
If you don't stop and look around
once in a while, you could miss it.

86
00:04:34,886 --> 00:04:37,684
I do have a test today.
That wasn't bullshit.

87
00:04:38,645 --> 00:04:42,285
It's on European socialism.
I mean, really, what's the point?

88
00:04:42,365 --> 00:04:45,524
I'm not European.
I don't plan on being European.

89
00:04:45,645 --> 00:04:47,804
So, who gives a crap
if they're socialists?

90
00:04:47,885 --> 00:04:49,444
They could be fascist anarchists.

91
00:04:49,525 --> 00:04:52,565
It still wouldn't change the fact
that I don't own a car.

92
00:04:55,446 --> 00:04:57,204
(SINGING DANKE SCHOEN)

93
00:05:10,126 --> 00:05:12,124
It's not that I condone fascism

94
00:05:12,405 --> 00:05:14,044
or any "ism," for that matter.

95
00:05:14,125 --> 00:05:16,404
"Isms," in my opinion, are not good.

96
00:05:16,765 --> 00:05:20,324
A person should not believe in an "ism,"
he should believe in himself.

97
00:05:20,406 --> 00:05:24,684
I quote John Lennon, "l don't believe
in Beatles, I just believe in me."

98
00:05:24,925 --> 00:05:28,085
A good point there.
After all, he was "The Walrus."

99
00:05:28,805 --> 00:05:32,244
I could be "The Walrus."
I'd still have to bum rides off of people.

100
00:05:33,205 --> 00:05:35,004
- Adams?
- Here.

101
00:05:35,165 --> 00:05:36,884
- Adamley?
- Here.

102
00:05:37,045 --> 00:05:39,124
Adamowsky?

103
00:05:39,206 --> 00:05:41,084
- Adamson?
- Here.

104
00:05:41,205 --> 00:05:43,844
- Adler?
- Here.

105
00:05:44,045 --> 00:05:45,004
Anderson?

106
00:05:46,005 --> 00:05:48,004
- Anderson?
- Here.

107
00:05:48,526 --> 00:05:55,484
Bueller?

108
00:05:56,885 --> 00:05:59,365
- Bueller?
- ADAMLEY: He's sick.

109
00:06:00,245 --> 00:06:02,724
My best friend's sister's
boyfriend's brother's girlfriend

110
00:06:02,805 --> 00:06:04,804
heard from this guy
who knows this kid, who's going

111
00:06:04,885 --> 00:06:08,164
with a girl who saw Ferris pass out
at Thirty-One Flavors last night.

112
00:06:08,245 --> 00:06:09,964
I guess it's pretty serious.

113
00:06:10,565 --> 00:06:13,324
- Thank you, Simone.
- No problem whatsoever.

114
00:06:13,645 --> 00:06:16,844
Frye? Frye?

115
00:06:18,965 --> 00:06:20,444
Frye?

116
00:06:26,165 --> 00:06:27,604
(PHONE RINGING)

117
00:06:28,166 --> 00:06:29,364
MAN: Hello?

118
00:06:29,925 --> 00:06:32,844
FERRIS: Cameron, babe,
what's happening?

119
00:06:32,925 --> 00:06:34,044
Very little.

120
00:06:34,125 --> 00:06:37,364
- How do you feel?
- Shredded.

121
00:06:37,605 --> 00:06:39,324
Is your mother in the room?

122
00:06:40,485 --> 00:06:43,724
She's in Decatur.
Unfortunately, she's not staying.

123
00:06:45,685 --> 00:06:46,684
Where are you?

124
00:06:46,765 --> 00:06:49,764
I'm taking the day off.
Now get dressed and come on over.

125
00:06:49,925 --> 00:06:51,804
I can't, stupid, I'm sick.

126
00:06:52,885 --> 00:06:53,884
That's all in your head.

127
00:06:53,965 --> 00:06:55,045
Come on over.

128
00:06:55,445 --> 00:06:58,364
I feel like complete shit, Ferris.
I can't go anywhere.

129
00:06:58,605 --> 00:07:02,484
I'm sorry to hear that.
Now come on over here and pick me up.

130
00:07:03,405 --> 00:07:04,364
Sheesh.

131
00:07:12,365 --> 00:07:13,564
I'm dying.

132
00:07:13,645 --> 00:07:15,124
(PHONE RINGING)

133
00:07:18,485 --> 00:07:19,444
(BUTTON CLICKS)

134
00:07:19,525 --> 00:07:22,804
FERRIS: You're not dying. You just
can't think of anything good to do.

135
00:07:25,165 --> 00:07:26,244
(BUTTON CLICKS)

136
00:07:26,325 --> 00:07:28,964
If anybody needs a day off,
it's Cameron.

137
00:07:29,365 --> 00:07:32,724
He has a lot of things to sort out
before he graduates.

138
00:07:32,805 --> 00:07:34,764
He can't be wound up this tight
and go to college.

139
00:07:34,845 --> 00:07:36,244
His roommate will kill him.

140
00:07:36,325 --> 00:07:40,884
(SINGING) When Cameron
was in Egypt's land

141
00:07:42,525 --> 00:07:46,564
Let my Cameron go

142
00:07:47,405 --> 00:07:49,804
Pardon my French,
but Cameron is so tight

143
00:07:50,005 --> 00:07:52,164
that if you stuck
a lump of coal up his ass,

144
00:07:52,245 --> 00:07:54,004
in two weeks you'd have a diamond.

145
00:08:00,485 --> 00:08:01,444
Katie Bueller.

146
00:08:01,525 --> 00:08:03,924
This is Edward R. Rooney,
Dean of Students.

147
00:08:04,085 --> 00:08:07,924
Oh, my God. I'm so sorry.

148
00:08:08,485 --> 00:08:10,684
I just completely forgot to call.

149
00:08:11,085 --> 00:08:13,764
ROONEY: Then you are aware
that your son is not in school today?

150
00:08:13,845 --> 00:08:16,124
KATIE: Yes, I am. Ferris is home, sick.

151
00:08:16,205 --> 00:08:17,764
Now, I had a meeting
first thing this morning.

152
00:08:17,845 --> 00:08:20,404
I know I should have called,
it just completely slipped my mind.

153
00:08:20,485 --> 00:08:22,204
I'm really very sorry.

154
00:08:22,645 --> 00:08:24,804
ROONEY: Are you also aware,
Mrs. Bueller, that

155
00:08:24,885 --> 00:08:27,524
Ferris does not have
what we consider to be

156
00:08:27,605 --> 00:08:29,604
an exemplary attendance record?

157
00:08:30,005 --> 00:08:31,404
KATIE: I don't understand.

158
00:08:31,565 --> 00:08:34,404
ROONEY: He has missed
an unacceptable number of school days.

159
00:08:35,125 --> 00:08:36,484
In the opinion of this educator,

160
00:08:36,565 --> 00:08:39,204
Ferris is not taking
his academic growth seriously.

161
00:08:39,964 --> 00:08:43,004
Now, I've spent my morning
examining his records.

162
00:08:44,485 --> 00:08:47,604
If Ferris thinks that
he can just coast through this month

163
00:08:47,725 --> 00:08:50,644
and still graduate,
he is sorely mistaken.

164
00:08:51,205 --> 00:08:53,924
I have no reservation, whatsoever,

165
00:08:54,085 --> 00:08:56,884
about holding him back another year.

166
00:08:58,445 --> 00:09:01,684
- This is all news to me.
- Usually is.

167
00:09:02,485 --> 00:09:06,404
So far this semester
he has been absent nine times.

168
00:09:07,885 --> 00:09:11,204
- Nine times?
- Nine times.

169
00:09:11,285 --> 00:09:13,644
I don't remember him
being sick nine times.

170
00:09:13,725 --> 00:09:17,444
That's probably because he wasn't sick,
he was skipping school.

171
00:09:18,605 --> 00:09:21,084
Wake up and smell the coffee,
Mrs. Bueller.

172
00:09:21,205 --> 00:09:22,404
It's a fool's paradise.

173
00:09:22,484 --> 00:09:25,444
He is just leading you
down the primrose path.

174
00:09:25,525 --> 00:09:26,724
I can't believe it.

175
00:09:26,805 --> 00:09:29,004
I've got it right here in front of me.

176
00:09:29,204 --> 00:09:30,964
He has missed nine days.

177
00:09:31,045 --> 00:09:32,244
(BEEPING)

178
00:09:39,805 --> 00:09:41,924
I asked for a car, I got a computer.

179
00:09:42,085 --> 00:09:44,484
How's that
for being born under a bad sign?

180
00:09:45,365 --> 00:09:46,804
Grace?

181
00:09:49,885 --> 00:09:51,364
Grace!

182
00:09:51,485 --> 00:09:54,484
Look, I can give you every assurance,
Mr. Rooney, that Ferris is home

183
00:09:54,565 --> 00:09:55,964
and he is very ill.

184
00:09:56,125 --> 00:09:58,484
In fact, I debated whether or not
I should even leave him.

185
00:09:58,565 --> 00:09:59,684
Grace!

186
00:09:59,765 --> 00:10:03,164
I can appreciate how this time of year
children are prone to taking the day off.

187
00:10:03,245 --> 00:10:07,924
However, in Ferris' case, I can
assure you, he is truly a very sick boy.

188
00:10:09,244 --> 00:10:10,804
(PLAYING OFF-KEY)

189
00:10:13,205 --> 00:10:14,644
Never had one lesson.

190
00:10:17,925 --> 00:10:19,204
In 1930,

191
00:10:19,285 --> 00:10:22,084
the Republican-controlled
House of Representatives,

192
00:10:22,165 --> 00:10:24,804
in an effort
to alleviate the effects of the...

193
00:10:25,125 --> 00:10:28,204
Anyone? Anyone?
The Great Depression,

194
00:10:28,685 --> 00:10:32,204
passed the... Anyone? Anyone?

195
00:10:32,765 --> 00:10:37,324
The tariff bill,
the Hawley-Smoot Tariff Act which...

196
00:10:38,565 --> 00:10:40,404
Anyone? Raised or lowered?

197
00:10:40,645 --> 00:10:42,443
Raised tariffs

198
00:10:42,724 --> 00:10:46,124
in an effort to collect more revenue
for the federal government.

199
00:10:46,684 --> 00:10:49,524
Did it work? Anyone?
Anyone know the effects?

200
00:10:50,245 --> 00:10:54,164
It did not work and the United States
sank deeper into the Great Depression.

201
00:10:54,644 --> 00:10:56,964
Today, we have
a similar debate over this.

202
00:10:57,045 --> 00:11:00,084
Anyone know what this is?
Class? Anyone?

203
00:11:00,725 --> 00:11:01,684
Anyone?

204
00:11:01,765 --> 00:11:03,364
Anyone seen this before?

205
00:11:03,605 --> 00:11:06,044
The Laffer Curve.
Anyone know what this says?

206
00:11:06,605 --> 00:11:08,484
It says, that at this point

207
00:11:08,565 --> 00:11:09,524
(CHALK SCREECHING ON BOARD)

208
00:11:09,604 --> 00:11:10,764
on the revenue curve,

209
00:11:10,844 --> 00:11:13,563
you will get exactly
the same amount of revenue

210
00:11:14,485 --> 00:11:15,844
as at this point.

211
00:11:15,925 --> 00:11:17,283
This is very controversial.

212
00:11:17,365 --> 00:11:21,044
Does anyone know what Vice President
Bush called this in 1980?

213
00:11:21,325 --> 00:11:22,524
Anyone?

214
00:11:23,285 --> 00:11:25,524
Something "d-o-o" economics.

215
00:11:26,204 --> 00:11:27,644
Voodoo economics.

216
00:11:27,844 --> 00:11:30,884
(JEANNIE (THEME FROM
I DREAM OF JEANNIE) PLAYING)

217
00:11:39,045 --> 00:11:40,364
Jeanie.

218
00:11:40,845 --> 00:11:42,564
I'm really sorry about your brother.

219
00:11:42,644 --> 00:11:45,364
What are you sorry for?
I have to live with the trouser snake.

220
00:11:45,445 --> 00:11:47,604
No, I mean, I heard he's really sick.

221
00:11:47,845 --> 00:11:49,844
Whoa. Whoa. Who said he's sick?

222
00:11:49,924 --> 00:11:53,004
A whole bunch of people. They said
he's like on the verge of death.

223
00:11:53,084 --> 00:11:54,804
This guy in my biology class

224
00:11:54,885 --> 00:11:58,963
said that if Ferris dies,
he's giving his eyes to Stevie Wonder.

225
00:11:59,644 --> 00:12:01,924
He's such a sweetie. Got to go.

226
00:12:02,964 --> 00:12:04,884
- Hi, Jeanie.
- Shut up.

227
00:12:06,244 --> 00:12:09,684
Please, do not yank my cord on this.
How desperate is the situation?

228
00:12:09,765 --> 00:12:11,443
Well, did you see Alien?

229
00:12:12,124 --> 00:12:14,644
When that creature
was in that guy's stomach?

230
00:12:15,925 --> 00:12:17,164
It kind of feels like that.

231
00:12:17,245 --> 00:12:18,244
(BEEPING)

232
00:12:18,324 --> 00:12:19,284
Freshmen.

233
00:12:19,445 --> 00:12:20,643
Goddamn, are you kidding?

234
00:12:20,725 --> 00:12:23,084
No, of course I'm not kidding.
Do I sound like I'm kidding?

235
00:12:23,165 --> 00:12:24,164
(SNEEZING)

236
00:12:24,245 --> 00:12:25,284
Who's he talking to?

237
00:12:25,365 --> 00:12:26,523
Ferris Bueller, do you know him?

238
00:12:26,605 --> 00:12:28,244
Yeah. He's getting me
out of summer school.

239
00:12:28,324 --> 00:12:30,284
BOY: We appreciate you letting us know
how you're doing.

240
00:12:30,364 --> 00:12:32,004
We've got to buzz.
Keep a good thought, dude.

241
00:12:32,085 --> 00:12:33,123
Thanks.

242
00:12:33,205 --> 00:12:34,164
(SNEEZING)

243
00:12:34,245 --> 00:12:35,884
Shit. I hope he doesn't die.

244
00:12:36,205 --> 00:12:37,764
I can't handle summer school.

245
00:12:37,845 --> 00:12:41,004
- Wait a minute, give me somebody else.
- Yeah, sure, hold on.

246
00:12:42,645 --> 00:12:45,043
- You see Alien?
- Yeah, why?

247
00:12:47,644 --> 00:12:49,644
- Hello?
- Hi.

